                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>CHARLES MUNNS. On the 28th of July, I was in Sydney's-alley. The officer came and asked me if I had had any thing taken from my pocket. I felt, and missed my handkerchief from my right-hand coat pocket. I had it about three minutes before - here it is; they had the prisoners in custody with it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-268-person1351">
                  WILLIAM 
                  COLTON
               <interp inst="t18250915-268-person1351" type="surname" value="COLTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-268-person1351" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-268-person1351" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . About half-past eight o'clock on the evening of the 28th of July, I saw the prisoners in the courts leading from Leicester-fields to St. Martin's-lane, following a gentleman; the prosecutor came by, and they pressed up against him. I saw Cowden do something, and then put something into his breeches and go away - they then took to the left hand, and the prosecutor the right. I sent Reardon to tell the prosecutor, and took the prisoners into a public-house. I then took off Griffin's hat and found the handkerchief.</p>
               <p>Prisoner GRIFFIN. Q. I was not in company with Cowden? A. Yes, you was for a quarter of an hour backwards and forwards through the courts. I had seen them in Long-acre before they saw the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-268-person1352">
                  DANIEL 
                  REARDON
               <interp inst="t18250915-268-person1352" type="surname" value="REARDON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-268-person1352" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-268-person1352" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was with Colton. I saw the prisoners first at the end of Long-acre; they went to the end of <placeName id="t18250915-268-crimeloc1439">St. Martin's-court</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-268-crimeloc1439" type="placeName" value="St. Martin's-court"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-268-crimeloc1439" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-268-off1437 t18250915-268-crimeloc1439"></join>. I then saw the prosecutor, and the two prisoners close behind him. I did not see them do any thing; but I saw them leave him at the end of the alley, and they turned off to Bear-street. I then went and told the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>COWDEN'S Defence. I was coming from work. I saw something on the ground, and kicked it before me. I then took it up, and saw it was a handkerchief. I met this young man at the corner of Bear-street, talking to a woman - I shewed it to him, and he said he would give me a pot of beer for it.</p>
               <p>GRIFFIN'S Defence. I live in Stephen-street, Tottenham-court-road. I met a young woman, and stood talking to her at the corner of Bear-street; the prisoner came to me, and said he had found this handkerchief, which he would sell. I said I would give him a pot of beer for it, and we were going to have it, when the officers came up and took us.</p>
               <p>COWDEN - <rs id="t18250915-268-verdict1440" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18250915-268-verdict1440" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 19.</p>
               <p>GRIFFIN - <rs id="t18250915-268-verdict1441" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18250915-268-verdict1441" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
